Would like the ability to edit the color scheme of plans and the capacity view, the two shades of green can be difficult to read and differentiate between, especially for people with vision issues.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1626].
  {panel}

Would really be helpful to be able to configure unique non-working day schedules per person and/or per team. That would make managing time off and global resources capacity so much easier than what is currently in place.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1625].
  {panel}

Currently, in Portfolio for JIRA, you are able to toggle between the Story, Epic and higher hierarchical levels on the scope and schedule view. This is very useful, but for Epics and other parent issues that do not have a continuous schedule of implementing work underneath it, it can sometimes be misleading not being able to drill down to the child issues on the schedule view.
For example, an Epic may have one story in sprint 1 (a spike) and all it's remaining stories in sprints 20, 21 and 22, but the Epic schedule view will just show a single bar starting in sprint 1 and ending in sprint 22. It would be very useful if you could visualise the underlying work in some way, either by having the option to expand and view the child issues on the schedule, or by shading/adjusting the thickness of the issue bar to illustrate where the underlying work actually is.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1623].
  {panel}

Portfolio for JIRA allows you to visualise dependencies between issues in the schedule view, but it will only ever show you the blocking item/s and the blocked item/s for a given issue.
It would be nice to have the option to view the _whole dependency chain_ when clicking on an item, perhaps with the immediately preceding and following dependencies highlighted in a different shade to the rest of the dependency chain.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1622].
  {panel}

The 'Scheduled Range' option that is available in Live Plans is a useful way of filtering down on a portion of your plan, but it's also a slow and relatively clumsy way of doing so if you need to change it often, as it needs to do a refresh and load every time.
An on-the-fly zooming option would be much user friendly, such as a scrolling bar.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1621].
  {panel}

Relates to JPO-1218 and JPO-83

A 'plan-of-plans' view should be available that pulls together scheduling information from multiple plans, possibly as a read-only report.
This would be invaluable not only to view dependencies between plans (see JPO-1218 and JPO-83) but also to view and compare higher-level shared information between the plans e.g. if teams share releases and initiatives.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1618].
  {panel}

There is currently a Progress column in the scope view which allows you to visualise the progress of an issue (or sum or issues), but this would also be very useful on the schedule view. 
An option to toggle this on and off would be very useful, as there was in v1.0 of Portfolio.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1615].
  {panel}

I want a way to view a calendar with a specified date range and see all the absences and/or exceptions that have been entered for a specified team in that date range.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1614].
  {panel}

I would like a way to add recurring absences and/or exceptions per person. For example if I have team member A who works Monday-Thursday from 9-5, I would like a way to set up an absence or exception for them that they can enter once, and have it reoccur every week or two weeks or every month and so on. 

Rather than lowering their capacity from 40 hours a week to 32, because for some reason when doing that, the tool assumes that the individual is still working Monday-Friday just at 6.4 hours a day rather than Monday-Thursday at 8 hours a day.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1613].
  {panel}

Shared teams are only useful if your team is only working on one portfolio plan at a time.

If you are paralleling work on multiple plans, shared teams don't work because the plans don't take in to account that the team member won't have their full availability for the plan, only a portion of it. This means scheduling using shared teams is very unrealistic. 

It would be best if it were possible to define how many hours per week a member of a shared team can actually dedicate to each plan.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1609].
  {panel}

Add a possibility to filter on empty or none to the filters on Release, Teams and Themes.
This makes it possible to find issues that do not have these fields filled in.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1608].
  {panel}

When creating new stories on a Plan, it would be helpful to have an option to enable the inheritance of some values - especially Team and Theme - from the parent issues according to Hierarchy.

Today, these fields are empty by default, which could cause confusion when using filters.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1607].
  {panel}

Love Portfolio!
However, the top blocker for us is the inability to have a Portfolio team be reflected into anything in Jira world. Having the ability to have a team map into anything which could be used in JQL (a component, a label, ...) would help tremendously.
End goal would be to associate a Jira board with a team in portfolio.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1605].
  {panel}

Our teams do high level planning and put High Level Estimates (HLEs) on Epics.  In classic plans, we could save that HLE in the Originally Planned field.  Once the story estimates were added, the Epic estimate would become a summation and we could compare our Originally Planned (baseline HLE) against the current estimate. If the current estimate was greater than the O.P. we knew we needed to make some adjustments to scope.

In Portfolio 2.0 Originally Planned is not available and with the way that Epic estimates  add the Epic + Child estimates, the Epic estimate is now overstating our estimates and we have no visual way to easily compare our original estimate with the current estimate without saving it off in another document and comparing it with what's in Portfolio. We really want the Originally Planned field back so that we can easily see when our current estimates are greater than our baseline estimates.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1604].
  {panel}

Under Reports and Themes, have multiple settings where we can show percentages by issue count. Within issue count, allow us to multiple select the issue type. This is helpful for kanban teams that do not track time nor do story points.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1603].
  {panel}

Allow multiple select of columns and bulk update for the Releases, Teams, and Themes Columns. Also, drop down selection should be alphabetical order to improve efficiency.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Portfolio Server*. Using *JIRA Portfolio Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JPOCLOUD-1602].
  {panel}

Sometimes, there are too many stories at the release level which causes a huge Gantt list on top of the road map. It would be very helpful for executive reporting to only show Epics and the option to not show at all and make the timeline larger/prettier so we can send it to our bosses. 

